00:03:20.530 --> 00:03:21.710
So a number of you.

00:03:21.710 --> 00:03:25.770
And ultimately, this
material-- no single factoid,

00:03:25.770 --> 00:03:30.030
but I think all of it together--
is a hugely complicating issue

00:03:30.030 --> 00:03:33.960
for notions of free will,
for notions of vulnerability,

00:03:33.960 --> 00:03:36.970
for notions of
culpability, all of that

00:03:36.970 --> 00:03:40.590
built around this question
often lurking between the lines,

00:03:40.590 --> 00:03:43.030
which is, why did
that behavior occur?

00:03:43.030 --> 00:03:44.760
Whose fault is it?

00:03:44.760 --> 00:03:46.870
As a boring subset
of that one is,

00:03:46.870 --> 00:03:48.530
why did this behavior occur?

00:03:48.530 --> 00:03:50.990
Who is worthy of praise for it?

00:03:50.990 --> 00:03:54.410
That one is ultimately equally
interesting, but probably less

00:03:54.410 --> 00:03:55.700
pressing in society.

00:03:55.700 --> 00:04:00.050
But where are these
behaviors coming from?

00:04:00.050 --> 00:04:02.500
And we've gotten
really good at doing

00:04:02.500 --> 00:04:05.160
some moderately
sophisticated things

00:04:05.160 --> 00:04:07.880
in dealing with the answer
to a question like these.

00:04:07.880 --> 00:04:11.960
And a great example of
that is with epilepsy.

00:04:11.960 --> 00:04:15.490
500 years ago, if you
had an epileptic seizure,

00:04:15.490 --> 00:04:19.540
where is this behavior coming
from was absolutely clear,

00:04:19.540 --> 00:04:22.520
which was demonic possession
of some sort or other,

00:04:22.520 --> 00:04:25.770
a staggering,
heartbreaking literature

00:04:25.770 --> 00:04:29.080
of the history of
treatments of epileptics

00:04:29.080 --> 00:04:30.910
and the response to epilepsy.

00:04:30.910 --> 00:04:34.980
If in the process of somebody
having a seizure 500 years ago,

00:04:34.980 --> 00:04:37.230
they flung their arms
around and struck

00:04:37.230 --> 00:04:39.380
somebody else in the
process, it would

00:04:39.380 --> 00:04:43.010
be considered some version
of assault and battery,

00:04:43.010 --> 00:04:45.190
in most of Western
European countries,

00:04:45.190 --> 00:04:48.160
again, explained with
a demonic underpinning.

00:04:48.160 --> 00:04:50.520
And we're in a
different position now.

00:04:50.520 --> 00:04:53.790
If today somebody has a
seizure and in the process,

00:04:53.790 --> 00:04:56.280
they strike and break
something, they're

00:04:56.280 --> 00:04:59.080
not to be held legally
responsible for if they

00:04:59.080 --> 00:05:00.500
strike somebody.

00:05:00.500 --> 00:05:02.080
That is not assault and battery.

00:05:02.080 --> 00:05:08.040
It is a ludicrous idea, because
somewhere around 1900 or so,

00:05:08.040 --> 00:05:10.740
most people in this
country got trained

00:05:10.740 --> 00:05:13.130
with a thought,
an explanation, a

00:05:13.130 --> 00:05:15.470
where did this
behavior come from that

00:05:15.470 --> 00:05:19.790
is as defining of everything
that is good about our culture

00:05:19.790 --> 00:05:20.490
world.

00:05:20.490 --> 00:05:23.780
Most people got to think
the following thing.

00:05:23.780 --> 00:05:26.840
It's not him, it's his disease.

00:05:26.840 --> 00:05:32.490
And that is a huge landmark
transition from 500 years ago,

00:05:32.490 --> 00:05:35.630
people being burnt at the
stake with some really

00:05:35.630 --> 00:05:40.000
bad attribution given to us
having the capacity to draw

00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:44.700
an absolute line between the
essence of who that person is

00:05:44.700 --> 00:05:49.020
and the action potential storms
that happen every now and then.

00:05:49.020 --> 00:05:51.940
It's not him, it's his disease.

00:05:51.940 --> 00:05:54.490
We're spectacular
at doing something

00:05:54.490 --> 00:05:56.370
like that with epilepsy.

00:05:56.370 --> 00:06:00.700
We are lousy at doing it in
all sorts of other domains.

00:06:00.700 --> 00:06:03.020
One example, schizophrenia.

00:06:03.020 --> 00:06:07.600
Back to schizophrenia again, and
the abnormal behaviors of it,

00:06:07.600 --> 00:06:10.900
and the occasional violence
associated with it, lower than

00:06:10.900 --> 00:06:13.790
in non-schizophrenia people,
but the occasional violence

00:06:13.790 --> 00:06:16.780
and, of course, the
classic case again,

00:06:16.780 --> 00:06:20.790
that guy John Hinckley trying
to kill Reagan in the 1980s.

00:06:20.790 --> 00:06:26.060
Paranoid schizophrenic,
floridly so, and that very wise

00:06:26.060 --> 00:06:29.840
jury of, in retrospect, some
remarkably unsophisticated

00:06:29.840 --> 00:06:33.920
people deciding, it's not
him, it's his disease,

00:06:33.920 --> 00:06:36.030
and put him in a
psychiatric hospital.

00:06:36.030 --> 00:06:39.600
And the apoplexy that
went through this country

00:06:39.600 --> 00:06:42.080
in response to with
the editorials,

00:06:42.080 --> 00:06:45.990
the senatorial
bloviating crap about,

00:06:45.990 --> 00:06:49.170
he's getting away with
this, he's getting away,

00:06:49.170 --> 00:06:53.520
he is responsible, showing
an utterly limited ability

00:06:53.520 --> 00:06:56.740
for people in this country, and
some extremely powerful ones,

00:06:56.740 --> 00:07:00.410
to draw a line between the
essence of who this John

00:07:00.410 --> 00:07:05.690
Hinckley is and the dopamine
abnormalities in his brain.

00:07:05.690 --> 00:07:09.570
And we have trouble drawing
that line as well, doe example,

00:07:09.570 --> 00:07:12.720
in the realm of
parents and teachers

00:07:12.720 --> 00:07:15.160
and guidance
counselors making sense

00:07:15.160 --> 00:07:18.530
of the biology of
learning disabilities,

00:07:18.530 --> 00:07:22.600
the biology of dyslexias, and a
whole world of people not very

00:07:22.600 --> 00:07:25.780
good yet at drawing a line
between that and the person.

00:07:25.780 --> 00:07:30.700
And instead, out come concepts
like lazy and stupid and things

00:07:30.700 --> 00:07:36.850
of that sort that have a
long, long well-maintained

00:07:36.850 --> 00:07:39.230
in the history of
education in this country.

00:07:39.230 --> 00:07:44.550
And a lot of people in positions
of power, parents et al, still

00:07:44.550 --> 00:07:46.590
have not gotten
very good at drawing

00:07:46.590 --> 00:07:50.100
the line between the essence
of who that person is

00:07:50.100 --> 00:07:52.400
and the biological
constraints that

00:07:52.400 --> 00:07:54.790
are superimposed on top of it.

00:07:54.790 --> 00:07:57.540
What you begin to see after
a while is something very

00:07:57.540 --> 00:07:59.090
interesting, which
is going to be one

00:07:59.090 --> 00:08:01.430
of the main points of
this last structure, which

00:08:01.430 --> 00:08:04.700
is, as more and more
information in this world

00:08:04.700 --> 00:08:07.960
of behavioral social
biology, whatever it is we're

00:08:07.960 --> 00:08:10.910
calling this, as more and
more of this has occurred,

00:08:10.910 --> 00:08:14.440
as we get more and more domains
where we have to at least begin

00:08:14.440 --> 00:08:18.200
to consider there's a line
in between the essence of

00:08:18.200 --> 00:08:21.280
and the abnormalities
of-- at some point,

00:08:21.280 --> 00:08:24.210
this is going to stop
being the biology of them

00:08:24.210 --> 00:08:28.280
and their disorders and is
going to be the biology of us.

00:08:28.280 --> 00:08:30.910
And when things get
really close to home

00:08:30.910 --> 00:08:33.360
at that point, that's
where a lot of people

00:08:33.360 --> 00:08:37.360
get very, very anxious
and very skittish about,

00:08:37.360 --> 00:08:39.330
essentially, the
punchline from a class

00:08:39.330 --> 00:08:42.490
like this, the
transition from them

00:08:42.490 --> 00:08:45.850
and their existing in
a different category

00:08:45.850 --> 00:08:49.410
with a boundary, with a
bucket, versus the rest of.

00:08:49.410 --> 00:08:51.690
Us as it gets closer
and closer to home,

00:08:51.690 --> 00:08:55.920
the transition from
them and disease to us

00:08:55.920 --> 00:09:00.410
and individual differences
and quirks and idiosyncrasies,

00:09:00.410 --> 00:09:05.360
and a biology that is just
as much of a biology as them

00:09:05.360 --> 00:09:09.150
and their diseases, where
the subtleties come in.

00:09:09.150 --> 00:09:12.050
And where there has to have been
that case, sort of that sense

00:09:12.050 --> 00:09:16.230
challenging, is looking at some
of the subtle neuropsychiatric

00:09:16.230 --> 00:09:18.910
disorders that we have in
the class, a few of which

00:09:18.910 --> 00:09:21.570
I'll go over again here,
but a few new ones,

00:09:21.570 --> 00:09:24.010
where over and over
it's the theme of,

00:09:24.010 --> 00:09:28.320
there's not that much
difference between me and them.

00:09:28.320 --> 00:09:31.320
I imagine exactly
what the continuum is.

00:09:31.320 --> 00:09:35.120
It is not clear whatsoever
where the line should be drawn,

00:09:35.120 --> 00:09:38.980
the new category of
normal versus abnormal.

00:09:38.980 --> 00:09:41.300
Case after case of this.

00:09:41.300 --> 00:09:44.100
One obvious one most
recently emphasized,

00:09:44.100 --> 00:09:47.850
schizotypalism, schizotypal
personality disorder.

00:09:47.850 --> 00:09:50.690
And when you look at
the range of symptoms,

00:09:50.690 --> 00:09:53.100
this is not a
psychiatric disorder.

00:09:53.100 --> 00:09:56.110
This really is not, and
justifies the transition

00:09:56.110 --> 00:10:00.200
to schizotypal personality,
rather than a disorder.

00:10:00.200 --> 00:10:04.310
It isn't a psychiatric disease
to consult astrologers.

00:10:04.310 --> 00:10:08.260
It isn't a psychiatric disease
to go to Star Trek conventions.

00:10:08.260 --> 00:10:09.770
It isn't any of these things.

00:10:09.770 --> 00:10:14.820
It is one extreme in one
axis of human behavior,

00:10:14.820 --> 00:10:18.100
and it is one where,
by definition, we're

00:10:18.100 --> 00:10:21.850
beginning to sense the biology
of it lurking around out there.

00:10:21.850 --> 00:10:25.590
We know it's got something
to do with the same genetics

00:10:25.590 --> 00:10:29.130
that you find in the fuller
loaded version in schizophrenia

00:10:29.130 --> 00:10:29.940
itself.

00:10:29.940 --> 00:10:34.650
We could begin to imagine
that this is the biology of us

00:10:34.650 --> 00:10:36.870
and some of our
quirky obsessions,

00:10:36.870 --> 00:10:39.960
versus them and
their schizophrenia.

00:10:39.960 --> 00:10:40.990
More examples.

00:10:40.990 --> 00:10:44.440
We endlessly heard about the
frontal lobe in this class,

00:10:44.440 --> 00:10:47.880
and we heard about the
boring, easy examples, when

00:10:47.880 --> 00:10:50.200
it is blown out
of the water, when

00:10:50.200 --> 00:10:53.490
you have Phineas Gage,
when you have frontally

00:10:53.490 --> 00:10:55.770
damaged disinhibited murderers.

00:10:55.770 --> 00:10:58.930
We've heard all about those,
and those are the easy ones.

00:10:58.930 --> 00:11:02.280
Those are not so easy if the
vast majority of states in this

00:11:02.280 --> 00:11:05.920
country cannot deal with the
notion at a criminal trial that

00:11:05.920 --> 00:11:10.170
somebody with no frontal cortex
is not a biologically normal

00:11:10.170 --> 00:11:10.800
human.

00:11:10.800 --> 00:11:13.400
But nonetheless,
that's relatively easy

00:11:13.400 --> 00:11:15.910
compared to the
issue that we really

00:11:15.910 --> 00:11:19.280
have to think about, which is,
the person sitting next to you

00:11:19.280 --> 00:11:22.080
has a different frontal
cortex than you do.

00:11:22.080 --> 00:11:24.570
And you, by now,
can come up-- yes,

00:11:24.570 --> 00:11:26.210
it's the person on
the left, seeing

00:11:26.210 --> 00:11:28.180
sort of where the
eyes are shifting--

00:11:28.180 --> 00:11:31.610
and coming up with
this obvious fact

00:11:31.610 --> 00:11:33.940
that this makes a difference.

00:11:33.940 --> 00:11:37.080
This makes a difference not in
explaining why one person here

00:11:37.080 --> 00:11:41.590
might be a serial murderer and
the next person not, but just,

00:11:41.590 --> 00:11:44.160
who's got it together
with the studying?

00:11:44.160 --> 00:11:46.770
Who's going to do an
all-nighter Thursday night?

00:11:46.770 --> 00:11:49.020
Who has what sort
of personality?

00:11:49.020 --> 00:11:51.580
Who is too shy to say
something or other?

00:11:51.580 --> 00:11:55.000
Who's the one who is
always the first to say--

00:11:55.000 --> 00:11:57.760
and this world of
individual differences.

00:11:57.760 --> 00:12:01.490
And you have no shortage by
now of ways in which that

00:12:01.490 --> 00:12:03.860
may manifest itself.

00:12:03.860 --> 00:12:06.260
How many neurons and
how many synapses

00:12:06.260 --> 00:12:08.490
and what sort of
receptors and all of that?

00:12:08.490 --> 00:12:11.810
You could go on all week long
as to the possible underpinnings

00:12:11.810 --> 00:12:13.870
of that, and you
could go on all week

00:12:13.870 --> 00:12:18.490
long as to what events--
genetic, prenatal, et cetera--

00:12:18.490 --> 00:12:19.880
might have brought that about.

00:12:19.880 --> 00:12:21.590
But the whole
critical thing there

00:12:21.590 --> 00:12:24.890
is the transition from
them and their brains

00:12:24.890 --> 00:12:28.690
with no frontal cortex left
to making sense of the fact

00:12:28.690 --> 00:12:32.220
that all of us with perfectly
normal frontal cortices

00:12:32.220 --> 00:12:34.780
nonetheless all
have different ones.

00:12:34.780 --> 00:12:36.800
And at some point,
this transition

00:12:36.800 --> 00:12:40.450
brings the term frontal,
frontal disinhibition, out

00:12:40.450 --> 00:12:42.380
of the realm of pathology.

00:12:42.380 --> 00:12:43.910
I mean, a great
example of this--

00:12:43.910 --> 00:12:46.350
in terms of how
commonplace this now

00:12:46.350 --> 00:12:49.070
is among of biological
psychiatry types-- you'll

00:12:49.070 --> 00:12:53.660
be at some conference, and some
poor, quivering grad student

00:12:53.660 --> 00:12:55.630
gets up to give a short talk.

00:12:55.630 --> 00:12:58.330
And this is the first
talk the person ever gave,

00:12:58.330 --> 00:13:01.140
and they're obviously like
a total nervous wreck,

00:13:01.140 --> 00:13:03.620
and they manage to sort
of limp through the end,

00:13:03.620 --> 00:13:07.850
and they're a sopping rag at the
end there, but they've done OK.

00:13:07.850 --> 00:13:11.740
And then some total jerk
big shot in the field

00:13:11.740 --> 00:13:14.960
gets up from the back
row and savages the guy,

00:13:14.960 --> 00:13:18.380
and gets him on stupid
statistics, minutiae,

00:13:18.380 --> 00:13:20.610
and chest thumps and
attacks his enemies

00:13:20.610 --> 00:13:23.790
and yells at him for not
citing, and going on and on.

00:13:23.790 --> 00:13:25.520
And somebody is
going to lean over

00:13:25.520 --> 00:13:27.140
to somebody else
in the audience,

00:13:27.140 --> 00:13:30.090
and referring to the
guy back, saying, jesus,

00:13:30.090 --> 00:13:32.940
he is getting more
frontal every day.

00:13:32.940 --> 00:13:36.080
And that may not
just be a metaphor.

00:13:36.080 --> 00:13:40.563
That may be a way of hinting at
the biology that is absolutely

00:13:40.563 --> 00:13:41.063
there.

00:13:41.063 --> 00:13:41.830
Why?

00:13:41.830 --> 00:13:44.600
Some of us do some things
like that, and some of us

00:13:44.600 --> 00:13:48.640
would die rather than be that
forward or that disinhibited,

00:13:48.640 --> 00:13:51.090
those individual differences.

00:13:51.090 --> 00:13:53.270
And we surely know
they are there,

00:13:53.270 --> 00:13:55.960
and we're beginning
to understand the baby

00:13:55.960 --> 00:13:59.610
steps of different versions
of dopamine receptors

00:13:59.610 --> 00:14:03.820
in the frontal cortex, that
whole world of transitioning

00:14:03.820 --> 00:14:06.740
from them and the front of their
head blown out of the water

00:14:06.740 --> 00:14:10.310
to us and our
individual differences.

00:14:10.310 --> 00:14:13.560
Another domain of this, another
realm of insight, and that's

00:14:13.560 --> 00:14:16.020
this disease
Huntington's Disease.

00:14:16.020 --> 00:14:19.260
And you will perhaps recall
back to the very first class,

00:14:19.260 --> 00:14:22.660
making reference to what turned
out to be Huntington's, what is

00:14:22.660 --> 00:14:26.160
very often the profile of
somebody with Huntington's.

00:14:26.160 --> 00:14:29.030
Middle aged guy
suddenly starts behaving

00:14:29.030 --> 00:14:32.470
in some outrageous way,
disinhibited, all of that,

00:14:32.470 --> 00:14:35.850
that whole business of,
there's behavioral features

00:14:35.850 --> 00:14:36.920
to this disease.

00:14:36.920 --> 00:14:39.890
Huntington's Disease is
a neurological disorder.

00:14:39.890 --> 00:14:43.510
Huntington's Chorea-- the
term chorea, choreography,

00:14:43.510 --> 00:14:46.770
body movement, Huntington's
uncontrolled writhing

00:14:46.770 --> 00:14:50.680
that eventually consumes
the entire body 24/7.

00:14:50.680 --> 00:14:53.180
The person eventually,
not so long,

00:14:53.180 --> 00:14:56.750
soon, dies from choking
to death on their saliva

00:14:56.750 --> 00:14:59.170
because their muscles
aren't coordinated any more.

00:14:59.170 --> 00:15:02.750
Totally horrile
neurological disease.

00:15:02.750 --> 00:15:05.010
But what has taken
people years is

00:15:05.010 --> 00:15:08.310
to realize that that's not
what Huntington's looks like

00:15:08.310 --> 00:15:09.610
at the beginning.

00:15:09.610 --> 00:15:13.250
And instead it's the profile,
the scenario that I gave

00:15:13.250 --> 00:15:15.640
in the very first class, again.

00:15:15.640 --> 00:15:18.580
Middle aged guy, happy
marriage, in the suburbs,

00:15:18.580 --> 00:15:22.840
jobs, 2.73 kids and dogs,
all of that sort of thing.

00:15:22.840 --> 00:15:26.090
And the one day he suddenly
punches somebody at work.

00:15:26.090 --> 00:15:29.920
Then the wife discovers he's
having an affair with whoever.

00:15:29.920 --> 00:15:33.070
Then he gets arrested for
brawling drunkenly in a bar

00:15:33.070 --> 00:15:34.410
and he never used to drink.

00:15:34.410 --> 00:15:37.620
And then he embezzles
all the funds from work

00:15:37.620 --> 00:15:42.510
and disappears forever, until
a year or two later, when

00:15:42.510 --> 00:15:45.900
he shows up in a neurology ward
at the other end of the country

00:15:45.900 --> 00:15:47.840
because he's getting tremors.

00:15:47.840 --> 00:15:49.620
And what people
have now figured out

00:15:49.620 --> 00:15:52.620
is, two or three years
before Huntington's is

00:15:52.620 --> 00:15:55.200
a neurological
disorder of movement,

00:15:55.200 --> 00:15:58.530
it's a psychiatric
disorder of disinhibition,

00:15:58.530 --> 00:16:00.800
and is one where
you begin to see

00:16:00.800 --> 00:16:03.300
a behavioral profile like this.

00:16:03.300 --> 00:16:05.560
And what you see is,
by the time you've

00:16:05.560 --> 00:16:07.400
got early stage
Huntington's patients

00:16:07.400 --> 00:16:09.180
when they're
hospitalized, they are

00:16:09.180 --> 00:16:12.190
famous for coming
on to the staffers

00:16:12.190 --> 00:16:15.690
or showing up in the day room
without their pajama bottoms,

00:16:15.690 --> 00:16:18.330
or just famous for
doing stuff like that,

00:16:18.330 --> 00:16:22.040
the disinhibited behavior
of Huntington's patients.

00:16:22.040 --> 00:16:24.680
And what's remarkable
there is, people have known

00:16:24.680 --> 00:16:28.210
for a long time what
the neuropathology is

00:16:28.210 --> 00:16:30.980
of Huntington's, Huntington's,
the movement disorder.

00:16:30.980 --> 00:16:32.860
And it's the disintegration
of some motor

00:16:32.860 --> 00:16:34.400
pathways in the brain.

00:16:34.400 --> 00:16:38.060
Now that people have genetic
markers for the disease,

00:16:38.060 --> 00:16:41.690
know with some likelihood who's
going to get it when, what's

00:16:41.690 --> 00:16:45.230
become apparent now is, two or
three years before you start

00:16:45.230 --> 00:16:47.510
getting damage in
the part of the brain

00:16:47.510 --> 00:16:50.330
having to do with motor
control, you get damage

00:16:50.330 --> 00:16:52.200
in the frontal cortex.

00:16:52.200 --> 00:16:55.090
Huntington's is
initially a disease

00:16:55.090 --> 00:16:58.590
of frontal cortical degradation.

00:16:58.590 --> 00:17:02.130
And what is remarkable
about that is,

00:17:02.130 --> 00:17:05.660
this is a genetic disorder
which immediately barrels us

00:17:05.660 --> 00:17:08.800
into the, this a
maladaptive trait.

00:17:08.800 --> 00:17:11.210
You are dead by the
time you're 50 or so.

00:17:11.210 --> 00:17:14.020
Our usual question,
why is it evolving,

00:17:14.020 --> 00:17:16.740
why is it being maintained
in the population,

00:17:16.740 --> 00:17:21.790
seeing a theme of a hidden
benefit of Huntington's, which

00:17:21.790 --> 00:17:24.970
is that disinhibited
behavior a couple

00:17:24.970 --> 00:17:28.440
of years before the
neurological symptoms do you in.

00:17:28.440 --> 00:17:31.170
During that time
window, individuals

00:17:31.170 --> 00:17:35.340
with Huntington's out-reproduce
their unaffected siblings.

00:17:35.340 --> 00:17:38.940
They become, among other
things, sexually promiscuous,

00:17:38.940 --> 00:17:41.670
and they pass on more
copies of their genes.

00:17:41.670 --> 00:17:43.470
And what you suddenly
see at that point

00:17:43.470 --> 00:17:46.650
is framed from the
standpoint of arms

00:17:46.650 --> 00:17:50.020
that won't stop moving-- we're
talking neurology-- framed

00:17:50.020 --> 00:17:53.330
from the standpoint of
number of copies of genes.

00:17:53.330 --> 00:17:55.510
This is an evolutionary advance.

00:17:55.510 --> 00:17:57.540
This is something
which behaviorally

00:17:57.540 --> 00:17:59.750
increases reproductive success.

00:17:59.750 --> 00:18:02.270
Onset is typically
around age 40,

00:18:02.270 --> 00:18:04.770
so catching it around that
time, which is typically

00:18:04.770 --> 00:18:07.790
around the point where
reproductive activity--

00:18:07.790 --> 00:18:09.940
reproduction goes
down in humans.

00:18:09.940 --> 00:18:12.320
So getting an extra
little blip out there

00:18:12.320 --> 00:18:14.730
from the standpoint of an
evolutionary biologist,

00:18:14.730 --> 00:18:16.280
this isn't a disease.

00:18:16.280 --> 00:18:19.900
This is a great invention
where the bill happens

00:18:19.900 --> 00:18:23.130
to come a while later, but
there is no free lunch.

00:18:23.130 --> 00:18:25.810
And framed that way, this
was a very different way

00:18:25.810 --> 00:18:27.220
of thinking about this disease.

00:18:27.220 --> 00:18:31.090
But what was most striking is,
when you first hear about it

00:18:31.090 --> 00:18:33.450
and somebody says,
OK, what do you

00:18:33.450 --> 00:18:36.690
think the causes of
this behavior are?

00:18:36.690 --> 00:18:38.290
What causes this?

00:18:38.290 --> 00:18:40.830
And the ones that most
readily come to mind

00:18:40.830 --> 00:18:42.840
is, the guy's a jerk.

00:18:42.840 --> 00:18:44.370
The guy's having
a midlife crisis.

00:18:44.370 --> 00:18:46.750
The guy's what,
like, oh, no, it's

00:18:46.750 --> 00:18:49.095
actually a single
gene defect where

00:18:49.095 --> 00:18:51.270
there's too many glutamines.

00:18:51.270 --> 00:18:56.660
That, and it's a disease of
a single gene goes wrong,

00:18:56.660 --> 00:18:58.170
and out comes this.

00:18:58.170 --> 00:19:01.350
And we need to
consider is, there's

00:19:01.350 --> 00:19:04.570
individual variation in
aspects of that system

00:19:04.570 --> 00:19:09.410
long, far outside the range of
what would get a disease label.

00:19:09.410 --> 00:19:12.130
And it doesn't take too
much imagination, again,

00:19:12.130 --> 00:19:15.610
to translate that into why
the person sitting next to you

00:19:15.610 --> 00:19:18.910
is a little more this way
and a little less that way.

00:19:18.910 --> 00:19:22.770
Just the same challenge
for us going from them

00:19:22.770 --> 00:19:25.000
to what makes us, us.

00:19:25.000 --> 00:19:26.360
Next example.

00:19:26.360 --> 00:19:29.810
Disease I've only briefly
mentioned, I think, previously.

00:19:29.810 --> 00:19:31.270
Tourette's disease.

00:19:31.270 --> 00:19:32.710
Tourette's disease.

00:19:32.710 --> 00:19:34.970
Everybody knows about
Tourette's disease,

00:19:34.970 --> 00:19:36.730
which is, it's
this disease where

00:19:36.730 --> 00:19:39.226
people curse uncontrollably.

00:19:39.226 --> 00:19:40.930
Scatology.

00:19:40.930 --> 00:19:43.840
Tourette's disease,
that doesn't begin to

00:19:43.840 --> 00:19:46.610
scratch the surface of
what Tourette's is about.

00:19:46.610 --> 00:19:49.640
With Tourette's, yes,
you get that scatology.

00:19:49.640 --> 00:19:54.630
You also get inappropriate
gesturing, tics, facial tics,

00:19:54.630 --> 00:19:57.510
gestures of all sorts,
aggressive ones,

00:19:57.510 --> 00:20:01.720
sexually inappropriate ones,
all sorts of vocalizations,

00:20:01.720 --> 00:20:04.050
barking sounds, animal sounds.

00:20:04.050 --> 00:20:08.500
It is just a torrent of
behaviors coming out.

00:20:08.500 --> 00:20:10.990
Now the critical thing when
looking at Tourette's is,

00:20:10.990 --> 00:20:13.670
this is different from
the inappropriate behavior

00:20:13.670 --> 00:20:15.530
of somebody with frontal damage.

00:20:15.530 --> 00:20:18.370
Frontal damage is
closer to home.

00:20:18.370 --> 00:20:20.910
Every single day, I
would bet all of us

00:20:20.910 --> 00:20:24.380
have thoughts that are boastful
or lustfall or petulant

00:20:24.380 --> 00:20:27.350
or whatever, where we
would die if anybody

00:20:27.350 --> 00:20:28.750
knew we were thinking that.

00:20:28.750 --> 00:20:32.350
And damage the frontal
cortex, and when you think it,

00:20:32.350 --> 00:20:33.720
you say it.

00:20:33.720 --> 00:20:37.350
It is not the secret desire
of every Tourette's patient

00:20:37.350 --> 00:20:40.460
to bark like a dog and
make quacking sounds once

00:20:40.460 --> 00:20:41.890
every seven seconds.

00:20:41.890 --> 00:20:44.220
And finally, thanks to the
damage of that disease,

00:20:44.220 --> 00:20:46.150
they are disinhibited to do so.

00:20:46.150 --> 00:20:50.290
This is an astonishingly clear
example of a line between

00:20:50.290 --> 00:20:54.420
the essence of who that person
is and these weird hiccups

00:20:54.420 --> 00:20:58.200
of the id that occur in the
limbic system with Tourette's.

00:20:58.200 --> 00:21:03.150
And again, in its milder
form, it's not a disease.

00:21:03.150 --> 00:21:05.650
It's individual variation.

00:21:05.650 --> 00:21:08.406
Now remarkably with
Tourette's, of course,

00:21:08.406 --> 00:21:10.030
people are beginning
to learn something

00:21:10.030 --> 00:21:11.650
about the biology of it.

00:21:11.650 --> 00:21:12.950
There's a genetic component.

00:21:12.950 --> 00:21:14.700
It's probably not that strong.

00:21:14.700 --> 00:21:17.240
Beginning to see brain
imaging correlates of it.

00:21:17.240 --> 00:21:21.880
One totally weird possible way
to wind up with Tourette's, and

00:21:21.880 --> 00:21:25.150
this is a brand new class
of pediatric diseases called

00:21:25.150 --> 00:21:28.340
PANDAS, PANDAS
diseases, which stands

00:21:28.340 --> 00:21:31.900
for-- do not write this down--
which stands for Pediatric

00:21:31.900 --> 00:21:34.750
Autoimmune Neuropsychological
Disorders Associated

00:21:34.750 --> 00:21:36.600
with Streptococcus.

00:21:36.600 --> 00:21:37.710
Here's what happens.

00:21:37.710 --> 00:21:41.060
You have a three-year-old,
four-year-old kid who gets

00:21:41.060 --> 00:21:45.350
a strep infection and runs a
high fever and winds up being

00:21:45.350 --> 00:21:49.400
the one in 10,000 kids in this
situation where something goes

00:21:49.400 --> 00:21:52.390
wrong, recovers from the
fever, everything is fine,

00:21:52.390 --> 00:21:56.640
and then two weeks
later explodes into tics

00:21:56.640 --> 00:22:00.860
and obsessive patterns and
Tourette's-like disinhibitions.

00:22:00.860 --> 00:22:03.490
And where did this come from?

00:22:03.490 --> 00:22:05.180
Totally paralyzing.

00:22:05.180 --> 00:22:08.200
And none of the
normal drugs work.

00:22:08.200 --> 00:22:11.500
And suddenly someone
stumbles on what does work.

00:22:11.500 --> 00:22:16.100
You give the child a drug that
suppresses their immune system.

00:22:16.100 --> 00:22:17.580
Things go back to normal.

00:22:17.580 --> 00:22:20.370
Then a couple years later,
they have some other fever

00:22:20.370 --> 00:22:23.590
and they spike a high
fever, and two weeks later

00:22:23.590 --> 00:22:26.660
they explode back
into these tics,

00:22:26.660 --> 00:22:29.990
these disinhibited behaviors,
these obsessions, all of that.

00:22:29.990 --> 00:22:31.530
What's going on?

00:22:31.530 --> 00:22:34.320
What appears to be the case
is in the subset of people

00:22:34.320 --> 00:22:37.810
with a high fever, these
kids, the blood brain barrier

00:22:37.810 --> 00:22:41.252
opens up in a way that
allows the immune system

00:22:41.252 --> 00:22:43.710
to get to places in the brain
where the immune system isn't

00:22:43.710 --> 00:22:44.720
supposed to be.

00:22:44.720 --> 00:22:47.280
And you form
antibodies that attack

00:22:47.280 --> 00:22:51.550
elements of your own brain,
of your own central nervous

00:22:51.550 --> 00:22:52.360
system.

00:22:52.360 --> 00:22:55.300
And this is what turns
out to be the case.

00:22:55.300 --> 00:22:59.110
It appears to be, in some
cases, an autoimmunie disorder,

00:22:59.110 --> 00:23:02.820
the treatment being, give the
person immune suppressants.

00:23:02.820 --> 00:23:06.910
And when you look at adults with
Tourette's disease or adults

00:23:06.910 --> 00:23:08.950
with obsessive
compulsive disorder,

00:23:08.950 --> 00:23:11.260
they have far
higher than expected

00:23:11.260 --> 00:23:15.970
at chance levels appearance of
antibodies in their bloodstream

00:23:15.970 --> 00:23:18.750
against constituents of
their nervous system.

00:23:18.750 --> 00:23:21.470
And they have a higher
than expected rate

00:23:21.470 --> 00:23:23.361
of these childhood fevers.

00:23:23.361 --> 00:23:25.360
The sort of stuff we've
been getting throughout,

00:23:25.360 --> 00:23:29.950
groping at these strange
little pieces of making sense

00:23:29.950 --> 00:23:30.880
of this stuff.

00:23:30.880 --> 00:23:34.510
And have something like that,
and you wind up with a disease

00:23:34.510 --> 00:23:37.110
that has this bizarre array
of symptoms that you see

00:23:37.110 --> 00:23:38.500
in Tourette's.

00:23:38.500 --> 00:23:42.090
And some years ago, I actually
had somebody in this class who

00:23:42.090 --> 00:23:43.046
had Tourette's.

00:23:43.046 --> 00:23:44.090
And it wasn't bad.

00:23:44.090 --> 00:23:46.410
He had like a few facial
tic sorts of things.

00:23:46.410 --> 00:23:48.110
And after the first
couple of classes,

00:23:48.110 --> 00:23:50.400
he came to office hours
and was kind of describing

00:23:50.400 --> 00:23:52.460
that he had Tourette's
and he was very glad

00:23:52.460 --> 00:23:54.105
that I was familiar
with his disease,

00:23:54.105 --> 00:23:56.230
and explaining that this
was sort of something that

00:23:56.230 --> 00:23:58.610
occasionally became
disruptive in classes.

00:23:58.610 --> 00:24:00.850
And if it would be possible,
it might make sense

00:24:00.850 --> 00:24:04.500
to have an exam in a sep--
and he spent the entire time

00:24:04.500 --> 00:24:06.150
doing this.

00:24:06.150 --> 00:24:07.500
This was the disease.

00:24:07.500 --> 00:24:10.300
This was the essence
of who he was.

00:24:10.300 --> 00:24:13.560
And you could not ask
for a clearer line.

00:24:13.560 --> 00:24:14.710
Look at this.

00:24:14.710 --> 00:24:17.320
500 years ago you have
Tourette's disease.

00:24:17.320 --> 00:24:20.350
It tends to have an adolescent
onset of the symptoms.

00:24:20.350 --> 00:24:23.730
It's got somewhat of a
bias female to male ratio.

00:24:23.730 --> 00:24:27.680
And certainly you've got a
13-year-old girl who suddenly

00:24:27.680 --> 00:24:32.280
starts cursing uncontrollably
with bizarre sexual references

00:24:32.280 --> 00:24:32.980
or whatever.

00:24:32.980 --> 00:24:35.790
And what's the only
possible conclusion?

00:24:35.790 --> 00:24:38.090
You've got someone
possessed by the devil

00:24:38.090 --> 00:24:40.420
who should be treated
appropriately.

00:24:40.420 --> 00:24:43.740
Look at where we've
gotten to in 500 years.

00:24:43.740 --> 00:24:45.610
We've gone from taking
people like that

00:24:45.610 --> 00:24:48.100
and burning them at the
stake to letting them take

00:24:48.100 --> 00:24:50.120
the MCATs in a different
room from everyone

00:24:50.120 --> 00:24:52.930
else so they don't disturb
them with the barking.

00:24:52.930 --> 00:24:55.520
We've gotten real good, with
a disease like Tourette's,

00:24:55.520 --> 00:25:01.640
of drawing the line over the
disease and who the person is.

00:25:01.640 --> 00:25:04.840
That's a realm where we've
gotten a lot of progress.

00:25:04.840 --> 00:25:08.010
More of these subtleties,
again, what in some ways

00:25:08.010 --> 00:25:11.270
was one of the most challenging
pieces of the religion lecture,

00:25:11.270 --> 00:25:13.650
making sense of
have a brain that

00:25:13.650 --> 00:25:17.690
has uncontrolled epileptic
firing for a couple of minutes

00:25:17.690 --> 00:25:20.710
