00:26:23.410 --> 00:26:25.450
as is schizophrenia.

00:26:25.450 --> 00:26:27.900
And people are beginning
to learn something

00:26:27.900 --> 00:26:30.480
about the biology
of it, that link

00:26:30.480 --> 00:26:33.660
to childhood high fevers
and strep infection.

00:26:33.660 --> 00:26:36.480
Some evidence of
genetic component to it.

00:26:36.480 --> 00:26:38.960
There is first
neuroimaging being done.

00:26:38.960 --> 00:26:42.880
And you might remember that area
of the brain, basal ganglia.

00:26:42.880 --> 00:26:43.550
Or maybe not.

00:26:43.550 --> 00:26:45.630
Have I actually
mentioned basal ganglia,

00:26:45.630 --> 00:26:47.050
or have I just wished to?

00:26:47.050 --> 00:26:47.550
OK.

00:26:47.550 --> 00:26:48.460
Basal ganglia.

00:26:48.460 --> 00:26:49.300
Motor area.

00:26:49.300 --> 00:26:52.530
What people are beginning
to see is, in OCD,

00:26:52.530 --> 00:26:54.370
put someone in a
scanner, and there

00:26:54.370 --> 00:26:57.810
is increased metabolic
rate in the basal ganglia,

00:26:57.810 --> 00:27:01.060
this part of the brain
involved in movement,

00:27:01.060 --> 00:27:04.690
involved in making sense
of the compulsions,

00:27:04.690 --> 00:27:08.010
the need to tap a certain
number of times, the need

00:27:08.010 --> 00:27:11.810
to arrange the utensils so that
they are perfectly parallel.

00:27:11.810 --> 00:27:15.840
The need to-- it's like there's
an itch in the motoric systems

00:27:15.840 --> 00:27:16.670
there.

00:27:16.670 --> 00:27:19.740
And people are beginning
to understand that one.

00:27:19.740 --> 00:27:22.890
Take somebody with OCD and
treat them successfully.

00:27:22.890 --> 00:27:26.850
It's typically with SSRI's,
serotonin uptake inhibitors,

00:27:26.850 --> 00:27:29.380
which also work for
aspects of depression.

00:27:29.380 --> 00:27:32.300
Treat someone effectively,
and the metabolic rate

00:27:32.300 --> 00:27:35.720
in the basal ganglia
goes back down to normal.

00:27:35.720 --> 00:27:38.890
The pieces begin to fit there.

00:27:38.890 --> 00:27:41.210
Getting into even
stranger realms--

00:27:41.210 --> 00:27:44.290
because these diseases, by
now, have mostly even passed

00:27:44.290 --> 00:27:46.720
the disease of the
month TV special,

00:27:46.720 --> 00:27:48.680
they are becoming to
be understood so well.

00:27:48.680 --> 00:27:50.710
Then there's a whole
world out there

00:27:50.710 --> 00:27:54.920
of the most bizarre possible
diseases you can imagine.

00:27:54.920 --> 00:27:57.070
Here's one of my favorite ones.

00:27:57.070 --> 00:27:59.590
It's called Jerusalem Syndrome.

00:27:59.590 --> 00:28:01.020
This one is great.

00:28:01.020 --> 00:28:03.440
This is such a bizarre disease.

00:28:03.440 --> 00:28:05.280
Jerusalem Syndrome.

00:28:05.280 --> 00:28:08.370
Shockingly, you can only get
through Jerusalem Syndrome

00:28:08.370 --> 00:28:10.030
in Jerusalem.

00:28:10.030 --> 00:28:10.880
Here's what you get.

00:28:10.880 --> 00:28:12.088
It's gotten to be a rule-out.

00:28:12.088 --> 00:28:15.630
The person who gets it cannot
have problems with depression

00:28:15.630 --> 00:28:16.770
or anxiety.

00:28:16.770 --> 00:28:19.390
Rule out all the other
psychiatric disorders.

00:28:19.390 --> 00:28:21.530
It's a standalone diagnosis.

00:28:21.530 --> 00:28:26.200
Here's the sort of person
who gets Jerusalem Syndrome.

00:28:26.200 --> 00:28:29.480
An American, highly
religious Southern Baptist

00:28:29.480 --> 00:28:33.100
on their first trip
ever to the Holy Land.

00:28:33.100 --> 00:28:35.140
Two other requirements
that virtually

00:28:35.140 --> 00:28:36.660
are in every single case.

00:28:36.660 --> 00:28:40.150
The person has to be
relatively on their own.

00:28:40.150 --> 00:28:42.680
At the end of the day, they
are in a room by themselves,

00:28:42.680 --> 00:28:46.240
and they have to be having
huge problems with the jet lag.

00:28:46.240 --> 00:28:48.190
In other words,
they're up at all sorts

00:28:48.190 --> 00:28:50.650
of weird times of
day, and really

00:28:50.650 --> 00:28:52.570
in soggy shape because of that.

00:28:52.570 --> 00:28:54.020
Here's what happens.

00:28:54.020 --> 00:28:57.010
This is the person who's been
waiting their entire life

00:28:57.010 --> 00:28:59.710
to finally come to the
Holy Land, has been saving,

00:28:59.710 --> 00:29:00.610
has been whatever.

00:29:00.610 --> 00:29:01.760
They scrape together.

00:29:01.760 --> 00:29:02.840
They go there.

00:29:02.840 --> 00:29:05.300
This will be the land
where Christ walked.

00:29:05.300 --> 00:29:07.870
And they get there and
they see that Jerusalem

00:29:07.870 --> 00:29:09.660
is like a normal city.

00:29:09.660 --> 00:29:12.760
There's traffic jams,
there's smog, there's noise,

00:29:12.760 --> 00:29:14.850
there's pickpockets,
there's McDonald's.

00:29:14.850 --> 00:29:18.390
There's all of that, and
they're disappointed.

00:29:18.390 --> 00:29:21.130
They are shattered by this.

00:29:21.130 --> 00:29:24.730
And something comes
unhinged, and something

00:29:24.730 --> 00:29:27.045
comes unhinged in the
middle of the night there.

00:29:27.045 --> 00:29:29.170
They're not being able to
sleep alone in that room,

00:29:29.170 --> 00:29:32.110
dealing with this
shocking realization

00:29:32.110 --> 00:29:34.390
that the place they had
dreamt of their entire life

00:29:34.390 --> 00:29:35.630
doesn't exist anymore.

00:29:35.630 --> 00:29:37.640
And something cracks.

00:29:37.640 --> 00:29:38.980
Here's the detail that I love.

00:29:38.980 --> 00:29:40.710
In every single
one of these cases,

00:29:40.710 --> 00:29:44.560
the person rips apart
the hotel room bed,

00:29:44.560 --> 00:29:49.890
shreds the-- not the mattress,
the sheet-- shreds the sheet,

00:29:49.890 --> 00:29:52.160
takes their clothes off,
and before you know it,

00:29:52.160 --> 00:29:54.070
they're on a street
corner in Jerusalem

00:29:54.070 --> 00:29:56.500
dressed in a toga
preaching to everyone,

00:29:56.500 --> 00:29:59.300
telling them to go
back to simpler ways.

00:29:59.300 --> 00:30:02.120
The psychiatry SWAT
team from the hospital

00:30:02.120 --> 00:30:04.014
there shows up,
takes the person,

00:30:04.014 --> 00:30:06.430
puts him in the hospital there
for a couple of days or so.

00:30:06.430 --> 00:30:07.460
Their head clears.

00:30:07.460 --> 00:30:09.676
Ships them back to
Biloxi or wherever,

00:30:09.676 --> 00:30:11.300
and they never have
a problem with this

00:30:11.300 --> 00:30:12.690
again for the rest
of their life.

00:30:12.690 --> 00:30:16.980
They get 50 cases of
this a year in Jerusalem.

00:30:16.980 --> 00:30:18.880
This is a recognized syndrome.

00:30:18.880 --> 00:30:22.760
People publish papers
about Jerusalem Syndrome.

00:30:22.760 --> 00:30:24.670
It struck me, though,
that there is actually

00:30:24.670 --> 00:30:27.030
a very easy cure for it,
which is, in Jerusalem, in all

00:30:27.030 --> 00:30:30.250
the hotel rooms, if the sheets
always were plaid or something.

00:30:30.250 --> 00:30:33.420
Something about the white just
begs to be pulled into a toga,

00:30:33.420 --> 00:30:35.440
and that sort of pushes
them over the edge.

00:30:35.440 --> 00:30:37.770
But this is a real disease.

00:30:37.770 --> 00:30:39.170
More of these.

00:30:39.170 --> 00:30:40.620
Stendhal's disease.

00:30:40.620 --> 00:30:43.580
Stendhal disease you can
only get in its official

00:30:43.580 --> 00:30:45.530
form in the city of Florence.

00:30:45.530 --> 00:30:47.840
And Stendhal, the
well-known-- what

00:30:47.840 --> 00:30:52.100
was he, a philosopher or
writer or hockey player?

00:30:52.100 --> 00:30:53.260
Writer.

00:30:53.260 --> 00:30:55.290
Yes, the well-known writer,
thank you, Stendhal,

00:30:55.290 --> 00:30:59.740
who, describing the first
time he came to Florence,

00:30:59.740 --> 00:31:03.080
and this sense of
vertigo and nausea

00:31:03.080 --> 00:31:05.200
and complete loss
of control that

00:31:05.200 --> 00:31:10.170
came from seeing one too many
amazing, priceless, unmatchable

00:31:10.170 --> 00:31:13.680
frescoes, where you get
into a manic state from it

00:31:13.680 --> 00:31:15.070
and you can't take it anymore.

00:31:15.070 --> 00:31:18.020
And you come out
running like a wild boar

00:31:18.020 --> 00:31:19.770
through the streets of Florence.

00:31:19.770 --> 00:31:22.360
This occurs with some
regularity there,

00:31:22.360 --> 00:31:24.920
and this is termed
Stendhal Syndrome.

00:31:24.920 --> 00:31:28.130
There are papers written
about the subject.

00:31:28.130 --> 00:31:28.970
More of these.

00:31:28.970 --> 00:31:34.500
Then there is a disease
which, trichotillomania--

00:31:34.500 --> 00:31:36.630
these
impossible-to-pronounce ones,

00:31:36.630 --> 00:31:42.400
people who eat hair, people
who eat hair obsessively.

00:31:42.400 --> 00:31:44.397
Not just the anxious
version, sometimes,

00:31:44.397 --> 00:31:46.980
of somebody who's kind of like
chewing their hair when they're

00:31:46.980 --> 00:31:48.190
sort of anxious.

00:31:48.190 --> 00:31:52.850
But instead this is where a
person is pulling hair off

00:31:52.850 --> 00:31:55.070
of their brush in
order to eat it.

00:31:55.070 --> 00:31:58.320
They go over to someone's house
and they go to the bathroom

00:31:58.320 --> 00:32:01.270
and open up and find the
brushes and the combs

00:32:01.270 --> 00:32:03.240
there to pull the hair off.

00:32:03.240 --> 00:32:08.490
This is an incredibly disturbed
disease, where at an extreme,

00:32:08.490 --> 00:32:12.150
you get somebody who has
consumed so much hair that it

00:32:12.150 --> 00:32:13.910
forms a hairball.

00:32:13.910 --> 00:32:17.650
It blocks their stomach, and
this is life-threatening.

00:32:17.650 --> 00:32:20.610
It forms a plug of
hair with a long strand

00:32:20.610 --> 00:32:23.380
of it coming up the esophagus.

00:32:23.380 --> 00:32:25.600
And this is life-threatening.

00:32:25.600 --> 00:32:28.752
And you have to take
it out surgically.

00:32:28.752 --> 00:32:31.750
And it's this whole clot of
hair with this thing that

00:32:31.750 --> 00:32:33.390
was going up in the esophagus.

00:32:33.390 --> 00:32:35.650
And what is this disease called?

00:32:35.650 --> 00:32:39.050
It's called Rapunzel's
Syndrome because

00:32:39.050 --> 00:32:40.790
of the long stretch of hair.

00:32:40.790 --> 00:32:43.260
How weird is that?

00:32:43.260 --> 00:32:44.640
What is that about?

00:32:44.640 --> 00:32:47.070
Just imagine we start with
one of our charts here,

00:32:47.070 --> 00:32:50.960
and we say, steals hair from
friends' bathroom brushes,

00:32:50.960 --> 00:32:54.310
and sort of say, try to do
that one of working our way

00:32:54.310 --> 00:32:56.770
backwards of what happened
the second before,

00:32:56.770 --> 00:32:58.620
to evolution of whatever.

00:32:58.620 --> 00:33:00.500
How bizarre is that?

00:33:00.500 --> 00:33:04.700
That's like nothing compared
to the next two diseases,

00:33:04.700 --> 00:33:07.380
that are so hard to
pronounce I'm not even

00:33:07.380 --> 00:33:09.950
going to attempt to.

00:33:09.950 --> 00:33:12.290
Actually the first disease
is pretty run of the mill

00:33:12.290 --> 00:33:13.530
and pretty straightforward.

00:33:13.530 --> 00:33:15.980
The first of these
is merely the disease

00:33:15.980 --> 00:33:21.944
of people who can only become
sexually aroused by amputees.

00:33:21.944 --> 00:33:22.810
Whoah.

00:33:22.810 --> 00:33:23.710
OK.

00:33:23.710 --> 00:33:25.380
That's a little bit peculiar.

00:33:25.380 --> 00:33:28.200
That makes like the person
with it seem like the kid

00:33:28.200 --> 00:33:30.590
next door compared to this one.

00:33:30.590 --> 00:33:32.710
This is the disease
of someone who

00:33:32.710 --> 00:33:35.610
has a body dimorphism image.

00:33:35.610 --> 00:33:38.800
It's a body
integrative disorder.

00:33:38.800 --> 00:33:41.170
This is someone who,
their entire life,

00:33:41.170 --> 00:33:45.260
has believed they are meant
to have a limb missing.

00:33:45.260 --> 00:33:49.410
Their sense of themselves
involve them being an amputee.

00:33:49.410 --> 00:33:51.320
This is a real disease.

00:33:51.320 --> 00:33:54.840
This is a real disease
where people have websites

00:33:54.840 --> 00:33:57.410
where they communicate
with each other about how

00:33:57.410 --> 00:34:00.200
to have industrial
accidents, accidents

00:34:00.200 --> 00:34:03.780
that will remove a limb, where
it will look like an accident.

00:34:03.780 --> 00:34:06.720
There are secret physicians
who will do this.

00:34:06.720 --> 00:34:09.480
There was a paper in
a neuroethics journal

00:34:09.480 --> 00:34:12.270
a couple of years ago
by a physician arguing

00:34:12.270 --> 00:34:14.400
that one should be
willing to carry out

00:34:14.400 --> 00:34:16.929
the surgery on a person
who wants this done,

00:34:16.929 --> 00:34:20.159
because they will find a way to
do it disastrously otherwise.

00:34:20.159 --> 00:34:22.880
As termed by the person
who first described it,

00:34:22.880 --> 00:34:25.980
this is a new way of being mad.

00:34:25.980 --> 00:34:30.190
And this is terrain
like you cannot imagine.

00:34:30.190 --> 00:34:32.710
Finally, most
shocking of all, this

00:34:32.710 --> 00:34:35.480
was a case report a couple
years ago of somebody

00:34:35.480 --> 00:34:37.850
who had stroke damage
to the cortical area

00:34:37.850 --> 00:34:40.560
towards the frontal cortex,
but also a little bit in one

00:34:40.560 --> 00:34:41.350
other area.

00:34:41.350 --> 00:34:43.469
And as the case
report described,

00:34:43.469 --> 00:34:45.960
this person, in the
aftermath, became

00:34:45.960 --> 00:34:49.409
obsessed with polka music.

00:34:49.409 --> 00:34:50.219
Polka music.

00:34:50.219 --> 00:34:53.510
This was like some gang
member Hell's Angel guy

00:34:53.510 --> 00:34:56.670
who had, like, brain damage
after one brawl too many.

00:34:56.670 --> 00:34:58.710
And out the other
end, this is someone

00:34:58.710 --> 00:35:02.170
who's willing to slash you to
bits if you disagree with which

00:35:02.170 --> 00:35:05.440
is the best polka group coming
out of Krakow these days,

00:35:05.440 --> 00:35:06.290
or some such thing.

00:35:06.290 --> 00:35:11.420
The person spent a dozen hours
a day listening to polka music.

00:35:11.420 --> 00:35:13.500
What the hell is with that?

00:35:13.500 --> 00:35:14.000
what?

00:35:14.000 --> 00:35:15.000
Damage there?

00:35:15.000 --> 00:35:18.440
We're just seeing these
totally bizarre ways

00:35:18.440 --> 00:35:20.720
in which things can go wrong.

00:35:20.720 --> 00:35:23.790
Things can go wrong in
merely peculiar ways.

00:35:23.790 --> 00:35:28.310
Things can go wrong in ways
that destroy people's lives.

00:35:28.310 --> 00:35:30.480
So what are we to make
of things like this?

00:35:30.480 --> 00:35:33.990
This whole world of these subtle
neuropsychiatric disorders

00:35:33.990 --> 00:35:36.390
where, with each one of
them, it's easier and easier

00:35:36.390 --> 00:35:39.400
to imagine how it
translates into not them

00:35:39.400 --> 00:35:43.240
and their disease, but our
individual differences.

00:35:43.240 --> 00:35:45.950
One thing to appreciate
is that the majority

00:35:45.950 --> 00:35:48.600
of these that fall in
this category, they

00:35:48.600 --> 00:35:51.660
didn't even have
names 50 years ago.

00:35:51.660 --> 00:35:55.510
There wasn't a way of
describing, or even imagining,

00:35:55.510 --> 00:35:59.160
that biology could go wrong
in this particular way.

00:35:59.160 --> 00:36:01.220
And there weren't
even names for those.

00:36:01.220 --> 00:36:03.750
Most of these didn't
have names 10 years ago.

00:36:03.750 --> 00:36:05.730
And what's obvious
then is, there's

00:36:05.730 --> 00:36:08.180
no way the science
is going to stop.

00:36:08.180 --> 00:36:10.010
Just more and more
of these names

00:36:10.010 --> 00:36:13.060
are going to appear, more
and more of these syndromes

00:36:13.060 --> 00:36:14.050
and disorders.

00:36:14.050 --> 00:36:16.540
And at some point,
every single one of us

00:36:16.540 --> 00:36:19.250
is going to have two or
three of those labels.

00:36:19.250 --> 00:36:22.100
And what happens at
that point, because this

00:36:22.100 --> 00:36:25.090
is describing a
very close array of

00:36:25.090 --> 00:36:27.800
human individual variability.

00:36:27.800 --> 00:36:29.510
I do not have OCD.

00:36:29.510 --> 00:36:31.730
But I will count
stairs on occasion.

00:36:31.730 --> 00:36:35.360
I, during periods of
anxiety, will do that.

00:36:35.360 --> 00:36:38.610
Obviously I have only
one clothing style

00:36:38.610 --> 00:36:40.640
for the last 10 weeks.

00:36:40.640 --> 00:36:43.390
Every day, coming here, I
go through the same sort

00:36:43.390 --> 00:36:45.630
of rehearsal saying,
I am not going

00:36:45.630 --> 00:36:49.100
to start off the lecture today
by saying, OK, let's get going.

00:36:49.100 --> 00:36:51.270
And then I've done it again.

00:36:51.270 --> 00:36:53.500
And I don't have OCD.

00:36:53.500 --> 00:36:56.575
I have that weird, weird
compulsive behavior,

00:36:56.575 --> 00:36:58.250
or ritualistic ones.

00:36:58.250 --> 00:36:58.990
Obsessional.

