you to have a fantasy
while standing on line

00:38:21.080 --> 00:38:22.400
in the supermarket.

00:38:22.400 --> 00:38:25.880
It's the same biology
on the same continuum.

00:38:25.880 --> 00:38:30.130
And somewhere in there it stops
being them and their diseases

00:38:30.130 --> 00:38:33.100
and becomes us and who we are.

00:38:33.100 --> 00:38:34.930
So one of the
challenges with that

00:38:34.930 --> 00:38:37.260
is, what's going
to happen as we get

00:38:37.260 --> 00:38:40.100
more and more of these
names that describes us more

00:38:40.100 --> 00:38:42.940
and more, and we understand
the neurotransmitters

00:38:42.940 --> 00:38:45.830
and the early experience and
the genes and all the last 10

00:38:45.830 --> 00:38:46.330
weeks.

00:38:46.330 --> 00:38:48.440
And as we understand
more and more of that,

00:38:48.440 --> 00:38:51.380
something often
happens at that point,

00:38:51.380 --> 00:38:56.850
which is, people begin to get
real uncomfortable, real sense

00:38:56.850 --> 00:38:58.410
of being threatened.

00:38:58.410 --> 00:39:01.260
For this tremendous
fear that what

00:39:01.260 --> 00:39:05.770
if those scientists accidentally
go and explain everything

00:39:05.770 --> 00:39:09.790
when we're beginning to
see biologies of tastes

00:39:09.790 --> 00:39:12.720
and religion and who
likes risk and who

00:39:12.720 --> 00:39:15.560
is capable of being
faithful and who is not,

00:39:15.560 --> 00:39:18.610
and who has-- and this realm
with individual differences,

00:39:18.610 --> 00:39:21.680
and begin to see the
machinery underneath.

00:39:21.680 --> 00:39:24.970
Lots of people get
uncomfortable at that point,

00:39:24.970 --> 00:39:29.910
because it challenges one of
the pretenses that we all,

00:39:29.910 --> 00:39:32.210
virtually all,
desperately cherish,

00:39:32.210 --> 00:39:35.870
which is the notion that we
are utterly, utterly unique,

00:39:35.870 --> 00:39:40.480
that each one of us is this
flame of individuality that

00:39:40.480 --> 00:39:44.290
cannot be captured, that
cannot be constrained,

00:39:44.290 --> 00:39:48.260
that defines us, this
individuality that is just

00:39:48.260 --> 00:39:49.350
bubbling away there.

00:39:49.350 --> 00:39:52.110
And there go those scientists
learning more and more

00:39:52.110 --> 00:39:53.516
about less and less.

00:39:53.516 --> 00:39:55.850
And they may mess that up.

00:39:55.850 --> 00:40:00.230
They may wipe out that
sense of our uniqueness.

00:40:00.230 --> 00:40:02.860
And that worry was
perfectly encapsulated.

00:40:02.860 --> 00:40:05.030
This famous story,
science fiction story,

00:40:05.030 --> 00:40:08.530
by Arthur C. Clarke called
The Nine Billion Names of God.

00:40:08.530 --> 00:40:11.250
Wonderful metaphor for this.

00:40:11.250 --> 00:40:13.230
This is a bunch
of Tibetan monks,

00:40:13.230 --> 00:40:16.560
and apparently in some
branch of Tibetan Buddhism,

00:40:16.560 --> 00:40:19.400
there is a belief that God
has nine billion names,

00:40:19.400 --> 00:40:23.920
an obvious metaphor for the
unknowable, the unattainable.

00:40:23.920 --> 00:40:26.330
And in this story,
these monks team up

00:40:26.330 --> 00:40:28.420
with a bunch of
computer scientists

00:40:28.420 --> 00:40:30.440
with the greatest
computer around that

00:40:30.440 --> 00:40:35.100
they program to start
printing out the names of God.

00:40:35.100 --> 00:40:38.380
And what happens in the story
is, as it's cranking through

00:40:38.380 --> 00:40:41.530
and it is going to name the
nine billion names of God,

00:40:41.530 --> 00:40:45.110
as it cranks through this,
as each new name comes out,

00:40:45.110 --> 00:40:48.680
one of the stars in
the sky goes dark.

00:40:48.680 --> 00:40:52.960
And that's a perfect metaphor
for this fear that people have,

00:40:52.960 --> 00:40:56.790
which is, if inadvertently
scientists go and learn

00:40:56.790 --> 00:41:00.900
everything with each new
soulless factoid that turns us

00:41:00.900 --> 00:41:05.390
just into a bunch of equations
or biochemical pathways,

00:41:05.390 --> 00:41:09.150
that with each new factoid,
one of the stars in the sky

00:41:09.150 --> 00:41:12.400
will go dark as we lose
some of our individuality,

00:41:12.400 --> 00:41:15.780
as we lose some of what
makes us who we are.

00:41:15.780 --> 00:41:18.540
There is no reason
to worry about this,

00:41:18.540 --> 00:41:20.540
and this is for two reasons.

00:41:20.540 --> 00:41:24.260
First off, even if scientists
went and inadvertently

00:41:24.260 --> 00:41:27.260
explained everything,
that still would not

00:41:27.260 --> 00:41:29.010
take away the wonder of it.

00:41:29.010 --> 00:41:31.890
You can take a gazelle
leaping and turn it

00:41:31.890 --> 00:41:34.960
into a whole bunch of
biomechanical equations.

00:41:34.960 --> 00:41:37.780
You could turn Bach
into Kontrapunkt Rules,

00:41:37.780 --> 00:41:40.150
and that does not in
the slightest change,

00:41:40.150 --> 00:41:43.340
or should not in the
slightest change, our capacity

00:41:43.340 --> 00:41:46.050
to be moved intensely by them.

00:41:46.050 --> 00:41:49.660
And there's no reason why
something should lose its power

00:41:49.660 --> 00:41:53.310
simply because it turns out to
have layers of complexity that

00:41:53.310 --> 00:41:57.460
were not initially available
to us, which we slowly attain.

00:41:57.460 --> 00:42:01.260
It should not destroy that
sense in the slightest.

00:42:01.260 --> 00:42:03.670
The second reason why this
isn't something to worry about

00:42:03.670 --> 00:42:07.160
is, scientists are never going
to inadvertently go and explain

00:42:07.160 --> 00:42:09.610
everything about
everything, because we've

00:42:09.610 --> 00:42:11.440
seen throughout the
class over and over

00:42:11.440 --> 00:42:14.520
and over again, every time
one question gets answered,

00:42:14.520 --> 00:42:16.920
10 more get generated,
half a dozen

00:42:16.920 --> 00:42:18.580
of which are much
more interesting

00:42:18.580 --> 00:42:20.630
questions than you
started off with.

00:42:20.630 --> 00:42:22.640
It is a fractal.

00:42:22.640 --> 00:42:26.520
It is an infinite fractal
of knowledge to be attained.

00:42:26.520 --> 00:42:28.710
They're never going to go
and inadvertently explain

00:42:28.710 --> 00:42:29.410
everything.

00:42:29.410 --> 00:42:31.610
Wonderful quote
from the geneticist

00:42:31.610 --> 00:42:34.160
Haldane-- he's the one who
came up with two brothers

00:42:34.160 --> 00:42:36.270
are eight cousinss--
another one of these,

00:42:36.270 --> 00:42:40.910
where he once said, "Life is not
only stranger than we imagine.

00:42:40.910 --> 00:42:43.920
Life is stranger
than we can imagine."

00:42:43.920 --> 00:42:47.530
Scientists are never going to
inadvertently go and explain

00:42:47.530 --> 00:42:48.410
everything.

00:42:48.410 --> 00:42:52.190
The purpose of science is not to
cure us of a sense of mystery.

00:42:52.190 --> 00:42:55.860
The purpose of science is
to constantly reinvent it.

00:42:55.860 --> 00:42:58.780
So that's one realm in
which people are threatened

00:42:58.780 --> 00:43:01.300
by all the sorts of
knowledge and where

00:43:01.300 --> 00:43:04.900
this is going in terms of
describing the what makes us

00:43:04.900 --> 00:43:06.120
who we are.

00:43:06.120 --> 00:43:07.670
There is another
realm, not just the,

00:43:07.670 --> 00:43:10.870
what happens to our sense of
selfness, another realm of,

00:43:10.870 --> 00:43:12.660
what does society do with this?

00:43:12.660 --> 00:43:16.490
What does society do as we get
more and more of these terms

00:43:16.490 --> 00:43:19.570
and we understand more and
more where the gears are,

00:43:19.570 --> 00:43:22.700
where the controls are,
where the challenges are

00:43:22.700 --> 00:43:25.620
to the sense of autonomy
and agency in people?

00:43:25.620 --> 00:43:27.890
What's going to
happen at that point?

00:43:27.890 --> 00:43:31.790
What's clear is, if you are
poor or poorly connected,

00:43:31.790 --> 00:43:34.920
you are screwed, because as
more and more of these labels

00:43:34.920 --> 00:43:37.420
are given out, that's
just the excuse that's

00:43:37.420 --> 00:43:42.580
needed to deny you a job or
health care or fair housing.

00:43:42.580 --> 00:43:47.340
That is clearly an enormous
danger with knowledge of this.

00:43:47.340 --> 00:43:49.990
But hopefully what
happens instead,

00:43:49.990 --> 00:43:54.750
on a more optimistic note, is
somewhere in all these continua

00:43:54.750 --> 00:43:58.000
that this class was
about, you see, there

00:43:58.000 --> 00:44:01.140
but for the grace of God, and
a couple of neurotransmitters

00:44:01.140 --> 00:44:04.450
and three or four more
receptors, could go I,

00:44:04.450 --> 00:44:07.360
as you begin to see
a continua as you

00:44:07.360 --> 00:44:11.410
begin to see all sorts of
realms that are tragically

00:44:11.410 --> 00:44:12.370
done in biology.

00:44:12.370 --> 00:44:16.090
We have no trouble looking at
a schizophrenic and seeing,

00:44:16.090 --> 00:44:18.870
this is a disease,
and this is someone

00:44:18.870 --> 00:44:22.420
who needs our care and
forgiveness and protection.

00:44:22.420 --> 00:44:25.980
And we are in a world now where
people who obsessively count

00:44:25.980 --> 00:44:28.400
numbers eight hours
a day, we will

00:44:28.400 --> 00:44:31.920
have to be able to view that
as just as much a disease that

00:44:31.920 --> 00:44:35.290
is just as much deserving
of care and protection

00:44:35.290 --> 00:44:36.390
and understanding.

00:44:36.390 --> 00:44:38.935
With any luck, what all this
knowledge is going to do

00:44:38.935 --> 00:44:42.950
is force us to extend an
umbrella of protection,

00:44:42.950 --> 00:44:45.150
a realm of empathy,
into areas we

00:44:45.150 --> 00:44:47.790
could never have
dreamt of before,

00:44:47.790 --> 00:44:49.410
but never have dreamt of.

00:44:49.410 --> 00:44:51.960
The same exact
extent that if you

00:44:51.960 --> 00:44:54.870
took the wisest,
most compassionate,

00:44:54.870 --> 00:44:59.280
most introspective person
on earth from 500 years ago

00:44:59.280 --> 00:45:01.800
and told them
epilepsy is a disease,

00:45:01.800 --> 00:45:03.940
it would have made
no sense at all.

00:45:03.940 --> 00:45:05.450
And we are certainly
sitting here

00:45:05.450 --> 00:45:07.480
with a whole world
of things where

00:45:07.480 --> 00:45:10.530
it could make no sense to us
at all, where we will come

00:45:10.530 --> 00:45:13.960
to see that it has biological
components as strongly as any

00:45:13.960 --> 00:45:14.900
of these others.

00:45:14.900 --> 00:45:17.940
And we will have this
challenge of seeing

00:45:17.940 --> 00:45:21.750
that this is a realm not of
judgement, but of protection.

00:45:21.750 --> 00:45:23.720
And when we reach
that point, we will

00:45:23.720 --> 00:45:26.430
have discovered that
when we describe somebody

00:45:26.430 --> 00:45:29.740
as being healthy, when we say we
are healthy, what we are really

00:45:29.740 --> 00:45:33.420
saying is, we merely have the
same diseases that everybody

00:45:33.420 --> 00:45:34.690
else does.

00:45:34.690 --> 00:45:37.240
And with any luck,
out of this will come

00:45:37.240 --> 00:45:39.640
a great deal of compassion.

00:45:39.640 --> 00:45:40.140
OK.

00:45:40.140 --> 00:45:42.090
So that's where all
of this may play out

00:45:42.090 --> 00:45:44.460
in terms of the
challenge to people's

00:45:44.460 --> 00:45:47.060
sense of individuality,
what society

00:45:47.060 --> 00:45:49.470
should do with knowledge
like this as it emerges.

00:45:49.470 --> 00:45:51.710
What's probably
most important is

00:45:51.710 --> 00:45:55.590
what all this stuff means
in terms of impacting you

00:45:55.590 --> 00:45:58.230
and your interactions
in society,

00:45:58.230 --> 00:46:00.890
and what you will wind up doing.

00:46:00.890 --> 00:46:03.860
One of the irritating
themes, probably

00:46:03.860 --> 00:46:06.520
the most irritating concept
in this whole course,

00:46:06.520 --> 00:46:10.902
is the one of modulation,
these stupid if-then clauses,

00:46:10.902 --> 00:46:12.360
because what they
say over and over

00:46:12.360 --> 00:46:15.370
and over again is, just when
you think you've figured out

00:46:15.370 --> 00:46:19.170
what is causing behavior, oh no,
it's not actually causing it,

00:46:19.170 --> 00:46:22.130
it is amplifying the
preexisting tendency of this

00:46:22.130 --> 00:46:25.800
or damping or modulating or
imposing a contingent clause.

00:46:25.800 --> 00:46:28.254
Doesn't anything cause anything?

00:46:28.254 --> 00:46:29.920
It's like the entire
point of this class

00:46:29.920 --> 00:46:32.510
that nothing ever actually
starts a behavior.

00:46:32.510 --> 00:46:35.140
Everything is modulating, so
you could never figure out

00:46:35.140 --> 00:46:36.560
how stuff is actually working.

00:46:36.560 --> 00:46:39.940
Why does this have
to be so complicated?

00:46:39.940 --> 00:46:42.220
And one thing that
comes out of the,

00:46:42.220 --> 00:46:44.240
why does this have
to be so complicated

00:46:44.240 --> 00:46:47.640
is, why does it have to be
so difficult to do something

00:46:47.640 --> 00:46:50.200
helpful, then in
any of these realms?

00:46:50.200 --> 00:46:53.830
And I know for a fact that
a large majority of you

00:46:53.830 --> 00:46:57.340
have the desire to do that,
figuring in some of the things

00:46:57.340 --> 00:46:59.140
you want to do with
the rest of your life.

00:46:59.140 --> 00:47:01.150
And what is really
easy is to come out

00:47:01.150 --> 00:47:02.680
of a course like
this saying, it's

00:47:02.680 --> 00:47:04.720
really impossible
to change anything

00:47:04.720 --> 00:47:07.930
because it is so
incredibly complex.

00:47:07.930 --> 00:47:10.770
It is really hard
to do it because

00:47:10.770 --> 00:47:12.750
of how complicated it is.

00:47:12.750 --> 00:47:14.000
But it's not impossible.

00:47:14.000 --> 00:47:16.330
It's really hard
to do it because it

00:47:16.330 --> 00:47:19.960
will require not only
doing vast amounts of work

00:47:19.960 --> 00:47:22.710
of collecting vast
amounts of information,

00:47:22.710 --> 00:47:25.260
but then trying to
synthesize it and trying

00:47:25.260 --> 00:47:27.900
to intuit when you should
stop paying attention

00:47:27.900 --> 00:47:30.000
to the vast amounts
of information.

00:47:30.000 --> 00:47:32.970
It is doable, but it
will be incredibly hard,

00:47:32.970 --> 00:47:35.950
because down the line,
every time one of you guys

00:47:35.950 --> 00:47:38.140
will choose to try
to do something

00:47:38.140 --> 00:47:40.710
with a level of excellence
that comes to people here very

00:47:40.710 --> 00:47:43.660
easily, every time you
choose to do something,

00:47:43.660 --> 00:47:46.980
you are facto saying
no to 20 other things.

00:47:46.980 --> 00:47:50.000
And some of those other things
will be very, very important

00:47:50.000 --> 00:47:50.920
things to you.

00:47:50.920 --> 00:47:53.620
And those are tough
choices to make.

00:47:53.620 --> 00:47:56.340
And it will be doable but
hard because something

00:47:56.340 --> 00:47:59.750
that's probably utterly
inconceivable to you guys,

00:47:59.750 --> 00:48:03.120
but which is, at some point
you're going to get tired.

00:48:03.120 --> 00:48:06.760
And it gets a lot harder
to try to turn all of this

00:48:06.760 --> 00:48:09.860
into how can you
make things better.

00:48:09.860 --> 00:48:13.340
But you guys need to do that.

00:48:13.340 --> 00:48:14.850
Here's a story.

00:48:14.850 --> 00:48:16.510
And this was about my father.

00:48:16.510 --> 00:48:19.780
My father was an architect,
an architectural historian.

00:48:19.780 --> 00:48:24.060
And part of his career he
taught in NYU, but McCarthy Era.

00:48:24.060 --> 00:48:26.460
Things didn't work out,
and he wound up teaching

00:48:26.460 --> 00:48:29.140
in this crappy little
architectural night

00:48:29.140 --> 00:48:32.690
school in Brooklyn for
years and years on end.

00:48:32.690 --> 00:48:36.900
This was as flea-bitten of a
place as you can possibly get.

00:48:36.900 --> 00:48:39.480
And every now and then I would
go to see a lecture of his.

00:48:39.480 --> 00:48:41.970
And he was a
spectacular lecturer.

00:48:41.970 --> 00:48:43.410
And he would do this thing.

00:48:43.410 --> 00:48:45.000
One of the lecturers,
he's in there

00:48:45.000 --> 00:48:49.530
and he's putting up pictures of
the most beautiful, important

00:48:49.530 --> 00:48:51.380
buildings on earth,
and Versailles

00:48:51.380 --> 00:48:55.950
and the pyramids of Giza, and
this or that incredible palace,

00:48:55.950 --> 00:48:58.060
and all of that.

00:48:58.060 --> 00:49:01.040
And here's these guys sitting
in this night school who

00:49:01.040 --> 00:49:03.540
are, like, working as
draftsmen during the day,

00:49:03.540 --> 00:49:05.790
and this is really
a ragtag bunch,

00:49:05.790 --> 00:49:08.900
and putting up these pictures
of the most beautiful archi--

00:49:08.900 --> 00:49:12.130
and you know exactly what it
is to inspire these people,

00:49:12.130 --> 00:49:13.590
to move to the grid.

00:49:13.590 --> 00:49:15.470
And no, that's not
what he's doing.

00:49:15.470 --> 00:49:18.010
He's putting up these
pictures, and he's

00:49:18.010 --> 00:49:21.390
yelling at these people saying,
for too long architects have

00:49:21.390 --> 00:49:22.950
been whores of the wealthy.

00:49:22.950 --> 00:49:24.990
What they do is we
build their palaces,

00:49:24.990 --> 00:49:27.720
we build their mausoleums,
we build their forts.

00:49:27.720 --> 00:49:29.970
And there's Versailles and
there's the Giza and all.

00:49:29.970 --> 00:49:33.509
And I do not want to see you
being the whores of the wealthy

00:49:33.509 --> 00:49:34.800
and the whores of the powerful.

00:49:34.800 --> 00:49:37.070
You are to-- and
he's yelling at them.

00:49:37.070 --> 00:49:38.480
He's yelling at them about this.

00:49:38.480 --> 00:49:40.021
And these are folks
who they're going

00:49:40.021 --> 00:49:42.600
to be lucky if they do,
like, illegal garage

00:49:42.600 --> 00:49:45.600
extensions in Canarsie
in Brooklyn someday.

00:49:45.600 --> 00:49:47.475
And he's yelling
at them about this.

00:49:47.475 --> 00:49:49.260
And I'm sitting
there thinking, this

00:49:49.260 --> 00:49:52.170
is the stupidest
thing I've ever seen.

00:49:52.170 --> 00:49:55.600
And it took some time to
realize that no, in fact,

00:49:55.600 --> 00:49:57.740
this was not at all stupid.

00:49:57.740 --> 00:50:00.970
And in fact, this was
something remarkably respectful

00:50:00.970 --> 00:50:03.640
he was doing, because
he was saying to them,

00:50:03.640 --> 00:50:06.940
you have the capacity to sin.

00:50:06.940 --> 00:50:09.510
You have the
capacity to do wrong.

00:50:09.510 --> 00:50:13.240
And implicit in granting the
power to people like that,

00:50:13.240 --> 00:50:15.460
and also intrinsic
in that is, thus

00:50:15.460 --> 00:50:19.060
you have the capacity to
attain a state of grace

00:50:19.060 --> 00:50:21.230
through the work
that you will do.

00:50:21.230 --> 00:50:24.600
Great other story,
Robert Oppenheimer,

00:50:24.600 --> 00:50:27.810
when the first atomic bomb
was tested, and went off,

00:50:27.810 --> 00:50:31.730
made an amazing
statement, which is "Now

00:50:31.730 --> 00:50:35.560
even physics knows sin." and
the statement there being

00:50:35.560 --> 00:50:38.920
that even something
as abstract as physics

00:50:38.920 --> 00:50:44.360
can, on some metaphorical,
some secular level, know sin.

00:50:44.360 --> 00:50:47.480
Even within the realm of
putting together buildings,

00:50:47.480 --> 00:50:50.380
if you do it toadying
for the wrong people,

00:50:50.380 --> 00:50:53.030
this could count as
a state of sinning,

00:50:53.030 --> 00:50:55.120
and intrinsic in that
is the possibility

00:50:55.120 --> 00:50:58.930
of a state of grace, even in
worlds like being a physicist

00:50:58.930 --> 00:51:01.260
or being an architect.

00:51:01.260 --> 00:51:04.220
It's not hard to see
that one for you guys,

00:51:04.220 --> 00:51:06.770
though, because of
who you all are.

00:51:06.770 --> 00:51:09.160
All of you here are privileged.

00:51:09.160 --> 00:51:10.310
You are powerful.

00:51:10.310 --> 00:51:13.430
You will have powerful
resources and connections

00:51:13.430 --> 00:51:14.620
your entire life.

00:51:14.620 --> 00:51:18.830
And it will constantly intersect
with the last 10 weeks.

00:51:18.830 --> 00:51:22.230
And it is guaranteed that some
of you, at various points,

00:51:22.230 --> 00:51:26.000
will have 30 seconds to
decide with somebody in an ER

00:51:26.000 --> 00:51:28.140
who has taken a
vast amount of pills

00:51:28.140 --> 00:51:29.770
to try to kill themselves.

00:51:29.770 --> 00:51:31.700
You need to decide, is it them?

00:51:31.700 --> 00:51:33.110
Is it their disease?

00:51:33.110 --> 00:51:34.560
Is there even a boundary?

00:51:34.560 --> 00:51:37.600
Do I give the command
against their will

00:51:37.600 --> 00:51:39.460
to have their stomach pumped?

00:51:39.460 --> 00:51:42.340
Every one of you, at some
point, will make decisions

00:51:42.340 --> 00:51:45.630
about quality of life, if you
go into medical professions,

00:51:45.630 --> 00:51:47.780
as to when you pull a plug.

00:51:47.780 --> 00:51:50.200
Almost certainly,
some of you in here

00:51:50.200 --> 00:51:52.560
will be judges
someplace or other,

00:51:52.560 --> 00:51:55.480
wrestling with some of the
exact issues brought up.

00:51:55.480 --> 00:51:57.780
Some of you in here
will be legislators

00:51:57.780 --> 00:52:00.480
deciding how money
should be spent, what

00:52:00.480 --> 00:52:02.370
things money is a waste on.

00:52:02.370 --> 00:52:04.970
And you guys will be
in positions like that,

00:52:04.970 --> 00:52:08.170
because if anybody will
wind up with those powers,

00:52:08.170 --> 00:52:09.540
it will be guys.

00:52:09.540 --> 00:52:12.360
And if you remember
any of this stuff, what

00:52:12.360 --> 00:52:14.100
will seem the easiest
thing to remember

00:52:14.100 --> 00:52:19.150
is, it's so complicated, it
is impossible to fix anything.

00:52:19.150 --> 00:52:22.490
It is impossible to
make things better.

00:52:22.490 --> 00:52:25.660
And so I want to finish the
class with two final thoughts

00:52:25.660 --> 00:52:26.160
here.

00:52:26.160 --> 00:52:29.280
One is, even though
it's complicated,

00:52:29.280 --> 00:52:31.570
you've got to do something.

00:52:31.570 --> 00:52:34.590
Wonderful, cool thing I
heard about in archeology.

00:52:34.590 --> 00:52:37.030
And I don't know if this is
really true or urban legend.

00:52:37.030 --> 00:52:40.530
But when you excavate a site,
what you are supposed to do

00:52:40.530 --> 00:52:43.090
is excavate only
about half of it.

00:52:43.090 --> 00:52:45.230
You leave the other
half for the people

00:52:45.230 --> 00:52:47.820
in the future with better
techniques and better

00:52:47.820 --> 00:52:50.010
understanding, and
leave something

00:52:50.010 --> 00:52:53.460
intact there to keep from
your blundering hands.

00:52:53.460 --> 00:52:56.840
And the next person who then
excavates does only half,

00:52:56.840 --> 00:52:59.210
and half at every
juncture, saying,

00:52:59.210 --> 00:53:02.270
leave the possibility that
people will be thinking

00:53:02.270 --> 00:53:04.550
very differently in the future.

00:53:04.550 --> 00:53:06.250
Work with the
possibility that some

00:53:06.250 --> 00:53:08.810
of the things we feel
certain about right now,

00:53:08.810 --> 00:53:11.130
the smartest and most
compassionate of people

00:53:11.130 --> 00:53:14.820
500 years ago, felt that
way about epilepsy or things

00:53:14.820 --> 00:53:15.910
of that sort.

00:53:15.910 --> 00:53:17.650
It's complicated.

00:53:17.650 --> 00:53:19.640
Just because it's
complicated, that's

00:53:19.640 --> 00:53:22.100
not an excuse to do nothing.

00:53:22.100 --> 00:53:24.930
If anybody is going to do
it and make a difference,

00:53:24.930 --> 00:53:26.580
it will be you guys.

00:53:26.580 --> 00:53:31.090
The other final point is to
do in one last dichotomy, one

00:53:31.090 --> 00:53:34.800
last artificial bucket, one that
runs through this business way

00:53:34.800 --> 00:53:35.930
too often.

00:53:35.930 --> 00:53:39.560
You don't have to choose between
being compassionate and being

00:53:39.560 --> 00:53:40.880
scientific.

00:53:40.880 --> 00:53:42.980
So go and do both.

00:53:42.980 --> 00:53:44.310
And good luck.

00:53:44.310 --> 00:53:49.320
[APPLAUSE]

00:53:49.320 --> 00:53:52.560
